[src:csharp-dotnet/asynchronous-programming] The Task asynchronous programming (TAP) model provides a layer of abstraction over typical asynchronous coding.
[src:csharp-dotnet/asynchronous-programming] In this model, you write code as a sequence of statements, the same as usual.
[src:csharp-dotnet/asynchronous-programming] The difference is you can read your task-based code as the compiler processes each statement and before it starts processing the next statement.
[src:csharp-dotnet/asynchronous-programming] To accomplish this model, the compiler performs many transformations to complete each task.
[src:csharp-dotnet/asynchronous-programming] Some statements can initiate work and return a Task object that represents the ongoing work and the compiler must resolve these transformations.
[src:csharp-dotnet/asynchronous-programming] The goal of task asynchronous programming is to enable code that reads like a sequence of statements, but executes in a more complicated order.
[src:csharp-dotnet/asynchronous-programming] Execution is based on external resource allocation and when tasks complete.
[src:csharp-dotnet/asynchronous-programming] The task asynchronous programming model is analogous to how people give instructions for processes that include asynchronous tasks.
[src:csharp-dotnet/asynchronous-programming] This article uses an example with instructions for making breakfast to show how the `async` and `await` keywords make it easier to reason about code that includes a series of asynchronous instructions.
[src:csharp-dotnet/asynchronous-programming] If you have experience with cooking, you might complete these instructions **asynchronously**.
[src:csharp-dotnet/asynchronous-programming] You start warming the pan for eggs, then start cooking the hash browns.
[src:csharp-dotnet/asynchronous-programming] You put the bread in the toaster, then start cooking the eggs.
[src:csharp-dotnet/asynchronous-programming] At each step of the process, you start a task, and then transition to other tasks that are ready for your attention.
[src:csharp-dotnet/asynchronous-programming] Cooking breakfast is a good example of asynchronous work that isn't parallel.
[src:csharp-dotnet/asynchronous-programming] One person (or thread) can handle all the tasks.
[src:csharp-dotnet/asynchronous-programming] One person can make breakfast asynchronously by starting the next task before the previous task completes.
[src:csharp-dotnet/asynchronous-programming] Each cooking task progresses regardless of whether someone is actively watching the process.
[src:csharp-dotnet/asynchronous-programming] As soon as you start warming the pan for the eggs, you can begin cooking the hash browns.
[src:csharp-dotnet/asynchronous-programming] After the hash browns start to cook, you can put the bread in the toaster.
[src:csharp-dotnet/asynchronous-programming] For a parallel algorithm, you need multiple people who cook (or multiple threads).
[src:csharp-dotnet/asynchronous-programming] One person cooks the eggs, another cooks the hash browns, and so on.
[src:csharp-dotnet/asynchronous-programming] Each person focuses on their one specific task.
[src:csharp-dotnet/asynchronous-programming] Each person who is cooking (or each thread) is blocked synchronously waiting for the current task to complete: Hash browns ready to flip, bread ready to pop up in toaster, and so on.
[src:csharp-dotnet/asynchronous-programming] If you interpret these instructions as a computer would, breakfast takes about 30 minutes to prepare.
[src:csharp-dotnet/asynchronous-programming] The duration is the sum of the individual task times.
[src:csharp-dotnet/asynchronous-programming] The computer blocks for each statement until all work completes, and then it proceeds to the next task statement.
[src:csharp-dotnet/asynchronous-programming] This approach can take significant time.
[src:csharp-dotnet/asynchronous-programming] In the breakfast example, the computer method creates an unsatisfying breakfast.
[src:csharp-dotnet/asynchronous-programming] Later tasks in the synchronous list, like toasting the bread, don't start until earlier tasks complete.
[src:csharp-dotnet/asynchronous-programming] Some food gets cold before the breakfast is ready to serve.
[src:csharp-dotnet/asynchronous-programming] If you want the computer to execute instructions asynchronously, you must write asynchronous code.
[src:csharp-dotnet/asynchronous-programming] When you write client programs, you want the UI to be responsive to user input.
[src:csharp-dotnet/asynchronous-programming] Your application shouldn't freeze all interaction while downloading data from the web.
[src:csharp-dotnet/asynchronous-programming] When you write server programs, you don't want to block threads that might be serving other requests.
[src:csharp-dotnet/asynchronous-programming] Using synchronous code when asynchronous alternatives exist hurts your ability to scale out less expensively.
[src:csharp-dotnet/asynchronous-programming] Successful modern apps require asynchronous code.
[src:csharp-dotnet/asynchronous-programming] Without language support, writing asynchronous code requires callbacks, completion events, or other means that obscure the original intent of the code.
[src:csharp-dotnet/asynchronous-programming] The advantage of synchronous code is the step-by-step action that makes it easy to scan and understand.
[src:csharp-dotnet/asynchronous-programming] Traditional asynchronous models force you to focus on the asynchronous nature of the code, not on the fundamental actions of the code.
[src:csharp-dotnet/asynchronous-programming] The previous code highlights an unfortunate programming practice: Writing synchronous code to perform asynchronous operations.
[src:csharp-dotnet/asynchronous-programming] The code blocks the current thread from doing any other work.
[src:csharp-dotnet/asynchronous-programming] The code doesn't interrupt the thread while there are running tasks.
[src:csharp-dotnet/asynchronous-programming] The outcome of this model is similar to staring at the toaster after you put in the bread.
[src:csharp-dotnet/asynchronous-programming] You ignore any interruptions and don't start other tasks until the bread pops up.
[src:csharp-dotnet/asynchronous-programming] You don't take the butter and jam out of the fridge.
[src:csharp-dotnet/asynchronous-programming] You might miss seeing a fire starting on the stove.
[src:csharp-dotnet/asynchronous-programming] You want to both toast the bread and handle other concerns at the same time.
