[src:csharp-dotnet/asynchronous-programming] You still put the bread in the toaster and stare at the toaster until the bread pops up, but you can now respond to interruptions.
[src:csharp-dotnet/asynchronous-programming] In a restaurant where multiple orders are placed, the cook can start a new order while another is already cooking.
[src:csharp-dotnet/asynchronous-programming] In the updated code, the thread working on the breakfast isn't blocked while waiting for any started task that's unfinished.
[src:csharp-dotnet/asynchronous-programming] For some applications, this change is all you need.
[src:csharp-dotnet/asynchronous-programming] You can enable your app to support user interaction while data downloads from the web.
[src:csharp-dotnet/asynchronous-programming] In other scenarios, you might want to start other tasks while waiting for the previous task to complete.
[src:csharp-dotnet/asynchronous-programming] For most operations, you want to start several independent tasks immediately.
[src:csharp-dotnet/asynchronous-programming] As each task completes, you initiate other work that's ready to start.
[src:csharp-dotnet/asynchronous-programming] When you apply this methodology to the breakfast example, you can prepare breakfast more quickly.
[src:csharp-dotnet/asynchronous-programming] You also get everything ready close to the same time, so you can enjoy a hot breakfast.
[src:csharp-dotnet/asynchronous-programming] The System.Threading.Tasks.Task class and related types are classes you can use to apply this style of reasoning to tasks that are in progress.
[src:csharp-dotnet/asynchronous-programming] This approach enables you to write code that more closely resembles the way you create breakfast in real life.
[src:csharp-dotnet/asynchronous-programming] You start cooking the eggs, hash browns, and toast at the same time.
[src:csharp-dotnet/asynchronous-programming] As each food item requires action, you turn your attention to that task, take care of the action, and then wait for something else that requires your attention.
