[src:csharp-dotnet/asynchronous-programming] The process of making the toast is a *composition* of an asynchronous operation (toast the bread) with synchronous operations (spread butter and jam on the toast).
[src:csharp-dotnet/asynchronous-programming] The composition of an asynchronous operation followed by synchronous work is an asynchronous operation.
[src:csharp-dotnet/asynchronous-programming] Stated another way, if any portion of an operation is asynchronous, the entire operation is asynchronous.
[src:csharp-dotnet/asynchronous-programming] In the previous updates, you learned how to use Task or Task<TResult> objects to hold running tasks.
[src:csharp-dotnet/asynchronous-programming] You wait on each task before you use its result.
[src:csharp-dotnet/asynchronous-programming] The next step is to create methods that represent the combination of other work.
[src:csharp-dotnet/asynchronous-programming] Before you serve breakfast, you want to wait on the task that represents toasting the bread before you spread the butter and jam.
[src:csharp-dotnet/asynchronous-programming] The `MakeToastWithButterAndJamAsync` method has the `async` modifier in its signature that signals to the compiler that the method contains an `await` expression and contains asynchronous operations.
[src:csharp-dotnet/asynchronous-programming] The method represents the task that toasts the bread, then spreads the butter and jam.
[src:csharp-dotnet/asynchronous-programming] The method returns a Task<TResult> object that represents the composition of the three operations.
[src:csharp-dotnet/asynchronous-programming] This code change illustrates an important technique for working with asynchronous code.
[src:csharp-dotnet/asynchronous-programming] You compose tasks by separating the operations into a new method that returns a task.
[src:csharp-dotnet/asynchronous-programming] You can choose when to wait on that task.
[src:csharp-dotnet/asynchronous-programming] Up to this point, your code implicitly assumes all tasks complete successfully.
[src:csharp-dotnet/asynchronous-programming] Asynchronous methods throw exceptions, just like their synchronous counterparts.
[src:csharp-dotnet/asynchronous-programming] The goals for asynchronous support for exceptions and error handling are the same as for asynchronous support in general.
[src:csharp-dotnet/asynchronous-programming] The best practice is to write code that reads like a series of synchronous statements.
[src:csharp-dotnet/asynchronous-programming] Tasks throw exceptions when they can't complete successfully.
[src:csharp-dotnet/asynchronous-programming] The client code can catch those exceptions when the `await` expression is applied to a started task.
[src:csharp-dotnet/asynchronous-programming] In the breakfast example, suppose the toaster catches fire while toasting the bread.
[src:csharp-dotnet/asynchronous-programming] When you compile this code, you see a warning about unreachable code.
[src:csharp-dotnet/asynchronous-programming] After the toaster catches fire, operations don't proceed normally and the code returns an error.
[src:csharp-dotnet/asynchronous-programming] Notice that quite a few tasks finish between the time when the toaster catches fire and the system observes the exception.
[src:csharp-dotnet/asynchronous-programming] When a task that runs asynchronously throws an exception, that task is **faulted**.
[src:csharp-dotnet/asynchronous-programming] The `Task` object holds the exception thrown in the Task.Exception property.
[src:csharp-dotnet/asynchronous-programming] Faulted tasks throw an exception when the `await` expression is applied to the task.
[src:csharp-dotnet/asynchronous-programming] When code running asynchronously throws an exception, the exception is stored in the `Task` object.
[src:csharp-dotnet/asynchronous-programming] The Task.Exception property is a System.AggregateException object because more than one exception might be thrown during asynchronous work.
[src:csharp-dotnet/asynchronous-programming] Any exception thrown is added to the AggregateException.InnerExceptions collection.
[src:csharp-dotnet/asynchronous-programming] If the `Exception` property is null, a new `AggregateException` object is created and the thrown exception is the first item in the collection.
[src:csharp-dotnet/asynchronous-programming] The most common scenario for a faulted task is that the `Exception` property contains exactly one exception.
[src:csharp-dotnet/asynchronous-programming] When your code waits on a faulted task, it rethrows the first AggregateException.InnerExceptions exception in the collection.
[src:csharp-dotnet/asynchronous-programming] This result is the reason why the output from the example shows an System.InvalidOperationException object rather than an `AggregateException` object.
[src:csharp-dotnet/asynchronous-programming] Extracting the first inner exception makes working with asynchronous methods as similar as possible to working with their synchronous counterparts.
[src:csharp-dotnet/asynchronous-programming] You can examine the `Exception` property in your code when your scenario might generate multiple exceptions.
[src:csharp-dotnet/asynchronous-programming] The recommended practice is for any argument validation exceptions to emerge *synchronously* from task-returning methods.
[src:csharp-dotnet/asynchronous-programming] For more information and examples, see Exceptions in task-returning methods.
[src:csharp-dotnet/asynchronous-programming] Before you continue to the next section, comment out the following two statements in your `ToastBreadAsync` method.
[src:csharp-dotnet/asynchronous-programming] You can improve the series of `await` expressions at the end of the previous code by using methods of the `Task` class.
[src:csharp-dotnet/asynchronous-programming] One API is the WhenAll method, which returns a Task object that completes when all the tasks in its argument list are complete.
[src:csharp-dotnet/asynchronous-programming] Another option is to use the WhenAny method, which returns a `Task<Task>` object that completes when any of its arguments complete.
[src:csharp-dotnet/asynchronous-programming] You can wait on the returned task because you know the task is done.
[src:csharp-dotnet/asynchronous-programming] The following code shows how you can use the WhenAny method to wait on the first task to finish and then process its result.
[src:csharp-dotnet/asynchronous-programming] After you process the result from the completed task, you remove the completed task from the list of tasks passed to the `WhenAny` method.
[src:csharp-dotnet/asynchronous-programming] Near the end of the code snippet, notice the `await finishedTask;` expression.
[src:csharp-dotnet/asynchronous-programming] This line is important because `Task.WhenAny` returns a `Task<Task>` - a wrapper task that contains the completed task.
[src:csharp-dotnet/asynchronous-programming] When you `await Task.WhenAny`, you're waiting for the wrapper task to complete, and the result is the actual task that finished first.
[src:csharp-dotnet/asynchronous-programming] However, to retrieve that task's result or ensure any exceptions are properly thrown, you must `await` the completed task itself (stored in `finishedTask`).
[src:csharp-dotnet/asynchronous-programming] Even though you know the task has finished, awaiting it again allows you to access its result or handle any exceptions that might have caused it to fault.
